{"title":"ASR-EC BENCHMARK: EVALUATING LARGE LANGUAGE MODELS ON CHINESE ASR ERROR CORRECTION","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"There is no public benchmark for Chinese ASR error correction, making it hard to study and compare methods across diverse error types and utterance lengths.","method":"Construct ASR-EC by decoding four Chinese speech corpora (THCHS-30, AISHELL-1/2, WeNetSpeech) with two contrasting, industry-grade ASR pipelines—Kaldi-K1 (DNN-HMM with n-gram FST LM) and Kaldi-K2 (Zipformer-Transducer E2E), both pre-trained on 10k-hour Chinese speech—to generate erroneous transcripts. Split data into short (~13 chars) and long (~38 chars) subsets, cap zero-CER cases (keep 10%), and report substitution, deletion, and insertion error compositions, yielding two datasets (A*, B*) spanning varied difficulties."},{"problem":"How to effectively leverage LLMs to correct Chinese ASR errors given that naïve prompting tends to over-correct and degrade CER.","method":"Systematically evaluate three LLM adaptation paradigms for ASR EC: (1) prompting (zero-/few-shot) and a two-step multi-step prompting that first detects errors then corrects; (2) parameter-efficient fine-tuning using LoRA to adapt LLMs to the task; and (3) multimodal augmentation that feeds a multimodal LLM with concatenated encoded raw audio plus instruction and erroneous transcript, trained end-to-end. Experiments on ASR-EC with ChatGLM3, Qwen, Baichuan2, and Qwen-Audio show prompting is ineffective due to over-correction, LoRA fine-tuning substantially improves CER and mitigates over-correction, and multimodal augmentation achieves the best (state-of-the-art) CER across short/long/mixed subsets."},{"problem":"Multimodal LLMs (audio+text) are not tailored for ASR error correction out-of-the-box; it is unclear if targeted supervision can further reduce CER beyond standard ASR or vanilla multimodal ASR modes.","method":"Fine-tune the audio-text model Qwen-Audio on ASR-EC by training it to output corrected text from concatenated audio encodings and erroneous transcripts. Compared to ASR baselines and Qwen-Audio’s vanilla ASR mode, the finetuned model yields large CER reductions across short/long/mixed sets (Table 5), demonstrating that ASR-EC supervision significantly boosts multimodal LLMs; remaining irreducible errors (e.g., names/pronouns without context) indicate a lower-bound CER absent external knowledge."}]}
